"Phew!" Joe whistled. "I'll say we'd better take care of her!"\par
"Who sent her?" Frank asked, then read, " 'Rah-mud Ghapur, Washington, D.C.' Never heard of the man."\par
"Nor I," said Joe. "We'll ask Dad when he gets home."\par
As the expressman left, Frank opened the package. It contained several items which the boys decided were falconry equipment.\par
"Looks as though Mr. Ghapur expects us to become falconers," Frank declared. "But why?"\par
They searched for a note in the wrappings but found none. "We'll probably get a call or a letter of explanation," said Joe.\par
Frank agreed, adding, "In the meantime, let's learn something about falcons. Dad probably has some books on the subject in his study."\par
All this time the hawk, which was blackish blue with a black-barred creamy breast, had been sitting quietly in the crate, eying her new masters. Now she raised up, fluttered her wings, and cried \i keer, keer, \i0 as if she wanted action. The boys laughed as they carried the bird and its trappings through the hall and upstairs to Mr. Hardy's combination office and study.\par
Here the famous detective had several file cabinets of criminal cases and photographs of underworld characters. Frank and Joe, endowed with natural sleuthing ability, had had many opportunities\par
